context: In eastern Pennsylvania the Great Appalachian Valley, or <b3_0>Great Valley<b3_0/>, was accessible by reason of a broad gateway between the end of South Mountain and the Highlands, and many <b5_0>Germans and Moravians<b5_0/> settled here <a0_0>between the Susquehanna and Delaware Rivers<a0_0/> forming the Pennsylvania Dutch community, some of whom even now speak a unique American dialect of German known as the "<a1_0><b4_0>Pennsylvania German language<b4_0/><a1_0/>" or "Pennsylvania Dutch." These latecomers to the New World were forced to the frontier to find cheap land. With their followers of both German, English and Scots-Irish origin, they worked their way southward and soon occupied <a2_0>all of the Shenandoah Valley<a2_0/>, ceded by the <b6_0>Iroquois<b6_0/>, and <b7_0>the upper reaches of the Great Valley tributaries of the Tennessee River<b7_0/>, ceded by the Cherokee.
